{
  "doc_id": "53240",
  "text": "Metabotropic glutamate receptors (mGluRs) mediate the actions of the excitatory neurotransmitter glutamate. These class C receptors are characterized by a large extracellular amino-terminal glutamate binding region composed of two globular domains that form a distinctive \"venus fly trap\" (VFT) [CITATION_1] . The specific amino-terminal glutamate binding region has been identified as a stretch of 24 amino acids whose mutations affect glutamate affinity [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Adjacent to the VFT domain is a 70-amino-acid, cysteine-rich domain required for allosteric coupling between the VFT and the transmembrane domains [CITATION_4] . This region also participates in receptor dimerization via the formation of a cysteine bridge between receptor pairs, the disruption of which leads to receptor loss of function [CITATION_5] .",
